Introduction

In this project we are given a dataset containing information on the Jesuit higher education institutions around the world. Though the dataset is incomplete with many values missing for variables such as the founding date or address, there are enough observations to get a well-rounded picture of Jesuit higher education. In this project we will be creating visualizations of our data to know what Jesuit Education really looks like in different regions of the world. We will be looking at the different regions first and then looking at how those regions compare with other ones. Below is a map of all the Jesuit institutions around the world sorted by their respected region.

map=get_map(location="Italy",maptype="roadmap",source="google",zoom=1)
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=Italy&zoom=1&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=roadmap&language=en-EN
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Italy
JEmap=ggmap(map)
JEmap=JEmap+geom_point(data=latlon,
            aes(lon,lat,color=Region),size=2,alpha = 0.5)+theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
                 panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
                axis.text = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
                axis.ticks = element_blank())+ labs(title = "National Jesuit Schools")
print(JEmap)
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

A more interactive map is presented below.
latlon<-latlon[complete.cases(latlon),]
leaflet() %>% addTiles()%>%addCircleMarkers(data=latlon,popup=~Name,color=JE$colorcode)
## Assuming 'lon' and 'lat' are longitude and latitude, respectively

Africa

In this analysis we start with the region of Africa. We begin by sub-setting our data so that we are only looking at the schools located in the Africa region. In order to perform the analysis, we want to perform, we must only look at those variables which contain an observation in them, this way some outliers which occur due to a lack of data rather than an extreme case of data do not skew our results. We eliminate any non-needed variables such as city. We then eliminate all schools which do not have data submitted for their Undergraduate.Enrollment variable and their Staff variable. We create two new variables, “Student2Staff” and “Alumni2Student”, which represent the student to staff ratio and the alumni to student ratio respectively, two metrics which are commonly used to judge the effectiveness/atmosphere of a school.

AfricaJE <- subset(JE, Region=="Africa")
AfricaJE$Founded<-NULL
AfricaJE$City<-NULL
AfricaJE$State<-NULL
AfricaJE$Country<-NULL
AfricaJE$Zipcode<-NULL
AfricaJE$Schools<-NULL
AfricaJE$colorcode<-NULL
AfricaJE$CityCountry<-NULL
AfricaJE<-AfricaJE[apply(AfricaJE[c(4:5)],1,function(z) !any(z==0)),] 
AfricaJE<-AfricaJE[complete.cases(AfricaJE),]
AfricaJE$Student2Staff<-((AfricaJE$Undergraduate.Enrollment)/AfricaJE$Staff)
AfricaJE$Alumni2Student<-((AfricaJE$Alumni)/AfricaJE$Undergraduate.Enrollment)

Number of Alumni in African Jesuit Educational Institutions

In this first visualization let us look at the number of Alumni in each school in the African region. The first thing we notice is that there were only three schools in Africa which had completed datasets available online. We see that the highest number of Alumni at an African Jesuit institution is 750 alumni. The lowest number of alumni at a Jesuit education is zero. This could be due to an un-submitted observation, a ridiculously low graduation rate, or a new institution which has not had any students complete the program yet.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(rcdimple))
Africadimpleplot=AfricaJE%>%dimple(
    x = c("Name"), y = "Alumni",
    type = "bar",title='Number of Alumni in African Jesuit Educational Institutions' ,width=1000,height=400)%>%
  add_legend()
saveWidget(Africadimpleplot,file = "Africadimpleplot.html",selfcontained = TRUE)
Africadimpleplot

Number of Undergraduates in African Jesuit Educational Institutions

In this next visualization, we observe the number of undergraduates enrolled at each African institution. In the largest African institution there are 150 students enrolled in the program. In the smallest African institution there are 61 students enrolled in the program.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(rcdimple))

Region Summary

In this last section, we will be looking at the averages amongst all the regions. On average North America has the oldest universities. Africa contains the newest universities with their average founding date being 1983.

Regions<-JE
Regions[is.na(Regions)] <- 0
Alumni<-Regions %>% 
  group_by(Region) %>% 
  summarise(Alumni = sum(Alumni))
Staff<-Regions %>% 
  group_by(Region) %>% 
  summarise(Staff = sum(Staff))
Enrollment<-Regions %>% 
  group_by(Region) %>% 
  summarise(Undergraduate.Enrollment = sum(Undergraduate.Enrollment))
Regions <-Regions %>% 
  group_by(Region) %>% 
  summarise(Founded  = mean(Founded[Founded!=0]) )
Regions<-merge(x = Regions, y = Enrollment, by = "Region", all = TRUE)
Regions<-merge(x = Regions, y = Staff, by = "Region", all = TRUE)
Regions<-merge(x = Regions, y = Alumni, by = "Region", all = TRUE)
Regions$Student2Staff<-((Regions$Undergraduate.Enrollment)/Regions$Staff)
Regions$Alumni2Student<-((Regions$Alumni)/Regions$Undergraduate.Enrollment)
dt=datatable(Regions, options=list(pageLength = 6))
saveWidget(dt,file = "dt.html",selfcontained = TRUE)
dt
Regions$lon<-c(34.50852,136.032488,15.077554,-61.32685,-105.25512,76.45631)
Regions$lat<-c(-8.783195,18.741554,48.918997,-4.442038,54.525961,25.037640)
Regions$colorcode <- ifelse(Regions$Region=="South Asia", "yellow",
                ifelse(Regions$Region=="European Union", "green",
                ifelse(Regions$Region=="Latin America", "blue",
                ifelse(Regions$Region=="Asia Pacific", "orange",
                ifelse(Regions$Region=="North America", "red",
                ifelse(Regions$Region=="Africa", "purple",
                           NA  ))))))

leaflet() %>% addTiles()%>%addCircleMarkers(data=Regions,popup=~Regions$Undergraduate.Enrollment,color=Regions$colorcode,radius=~Regions$Undergraduate.Enrollment*.0005)

Staff

Latin America has the most average staff employed with 126,795 staff members. Africa again being the lowest with 100 staff members on average employed.

leaflet() %>% addTiles()%>%addCircleMarkers(data=Regions,popup=~Regions$Staff,color=Regions$colorcode,radius=~Regions$Staff*.005)
## Assuming 'lon' and 'lat' are longitude and latitude, respectively

Alumni

North America has the highest number of alumni with 1,560,401 average alumni. The lowest number of alumni belong to the African region with 2,776 average alumni.

leaflet() %>% addTiles()%>%addCircleMarkers(data=Regions,popup=~Regions$Alumni,color=Regions$colorcode,radius=~Regions$Alumni*.00005)

Student to Staff Ratio

The Asian Pacific has the highest ratio of students to staff with an average of 13.2 students. The lowest ratio belongs to Africa with the average of students per staff member being 3.1.

leaflet() %>% addTiles()%>%addCircleMarkers(data=Regions,popup=~Regions$Student2Staff,color=Regions$colorcode,radius=~Regions$Student2Staff*5)
## Assuming 'lon' and 'lat' are longitude and latitude, respectively

Alumni to Student Ratio

North America has the highest ratio of alumni to students with 14.1 alumni per student. The lowest ratio belongs to Latin America with 4.8 alumni per student.

leaflet() %>% addTiles()%>%addCircleMarkers(data=Regions,popup=~Regions$Alumni2Student,color=Regions$colorcode,radius=~Regions$Alumni2Student*5)
## Assuming 'lon' and 'lat' are longitude and latitude, respectively

Conclusion

In conclusion, we can say that Jesuit educational institutions located in the Latin American region tend to have the largest student bodies compared to other regions. Staff as well in the Latin American regions on average are higher compared to other regions of Jesuit educational institutions. The smallest in both these categories are those institutions located in the African region. In terms of the alumni and alumni to student ratio, we can conclude that North America has the highest number of alumni on average for Jesuit educational institutions. Institutions in Africa have the smallest alumni population, however it is Latin American Jesuit institutions which have the lowest alumni to student ratio. Lastly in terms of student to staff ratio, we can conclude that those regions in the Asian Pacific have the most students per staff. This is not good, as this means that the amount of students each staff member is accountable for is greater. The lowest student to staff ratio belonged to those institutions in Africa.

Limitations

If there was more complete data in this dataset we could have included not only more institutions in our map and analyses, but also could have included more variables to observe. For instance, we could have seen a much better analysis on the variable of Founded if we had more data. We could have also created a much more accurate map instead of just using the cities of the institutions of we had all of the addresses. With so many of the values equaling 0, we could have also seen a change in which regions had more alumni or students.
